I'll provide you with some examples of secure forms that demonstrate the principles I mentioned earlier. Please note that these examples are simplified and not intended for production use without proper validation and testing.

**Example 1: Secure Form with HTTPS and Input Validation**

```html
<!-- index.html -->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Secure Form Example</title>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/jquery@3.6.0/dist/jquery.min.js"></script>
</head>
<body>
    <form id="secure-form" method="POST" action="/submit">
        <!-- Input fields with validation -->
        <label for="name">Name:</label>
        <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required>
        <span id="name-error" class="error"></span>

        <label for="ssn">Social Security Number:</label>
        <input type="text" id="ssn" name="ssn" pattern="[0-9]{3}-[0-9]{2}-[0-9]{4}" required>
        <span id="ssn-error" class="error"></span>

        <button type="submit">Submit</button>
    </form>

    <script>
        // Validate input fields on submit
        $('#secure-form').submit(function(e) {
            e.preventDefault();
            var name = $('#name').val();
            var ssn = $('#ssn').val();

            // Check for valid name and SSN
            if (name.length > 0 && ssn.match(/^\d{3}-\d{2}-\d{4}$/)) {
                // Submit form data to server
                $.ajax({
                    type: 'POST',
                    url: '/submit',
                    data: { name: name, ssn: ssn },
                    success: function(data) {
                        console.log(data);
                    }
                });
            } else {
                // Display error messages
                if (name.length === 0) {
                    $('#name-error').text('Name is required');
                } else {
                    $('#name-error').text('');
                }

                if (!ssn.match(/^\d{3}-\d{2}-\d{4}$/)) {
                    $('#ssn-error').text('Invalid SSN format');
                } else {
                    $('#ssn-error').text('');
                }
            }
        });
    </script>
    </body>
</html>
```

**Notes:**

* The form uses HTTPS (via jQuery's CDN) to encrypt data transmitted between the client and server.
* Input fields have validation using HTML5's `required` attribute and a regular expression for the SSN field.
* The form submission is handled using JavaScript's `ajax` method to prevent page reloads and allow for more flexible form handling.

**Example 2: Secure Form with Hashing and Salting**

```php
// server.php
<?php
// Hash and salt user input
function hash_ssn($ssn) {
    $salt = 'my_secret_salt';
    $hashed_ssn = hash('sha256', $salt . $ssn);
    return $hashed_ssn;
}

// Handle form submission
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    $name = $_POST['name'];
    $ssn = $_POST['ssn'];

    // Hash and store SSN
    $hashed_ssn = hash_ssn($ssn);
    // Store hashed SSN in database
    // ...
}
?>
```

**Notes:**

* The server-side code hashes the SSN using a strong hashing algorithm (SHA-256) and a secret salt to prevent rainbow table attacks.
* The hashed SSN is stored in the database instead of the original SSN.

**Example 3: Secure Form with Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)**

```php
// server.php
<?php
// Define roles and permissions
$roles = array(
    'admin' => array('view_ssn', 'edit_ssn'),
    'user' => array('view_ssn')
);

// Handle form submission
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    $name = $_POST['name'];
    $ssn = $_POST['ssn'];

    // Check user role and permissions
    if (isset($_SESSION['role']) && in_array('view_ssn', $roles[$_SESSION['role']])) {
        // Display SSN to user
        echo $ssn;
    } else {
        // Display error message
        echo 'Access denied';
    }
}
?>
```

**Notes:**

* The server-side code uses RBAC to restrict access to sensitive data (SSN) based on the user's role and permissions.
* The user's role is stored in a session variable, and the server checks the user's permissions before displaying the SSN.

These examples demonstrate how to implement secure practices in forms, including HTTPS, input validation, hashing and salting, and role-based access control. Remember to adapt these examples to your specific use case and ensure proper validation and testing before deploying them in production.

